    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Clean, well-scoped fix. The root cause analysis in the PR description is thorough: every claim in it was independently verified by multiple reviewers against the code. The fix mirrors the production invalidation path exactly. No new abstractions, no scope drift.\n\nOne P3, one Nit. The P3 is about the helper lacking documentation about its cache-invalidation requirement, not about the fix itself.\n\n> \"insertEnabledAnthropicProvider is a shared helper with no cache awareness; the next caller who uses it after CreateChat will reproduce this flake.\" (Hisoka)\n\n\n---\n\n`coderd/x/chatd/subagent_internal_test.go:153`\n\n**P3** [DEREM-1] The doc comment on `insertEnabledAnthropicProvider` doesn't mention that this helper bypasses the pubsub event production uses to invalidate `configCache`. Any future test that calls this helper after `CreateChat` (which triggers cache population via `signalWake`) will hit the same stale-cache flake that this PR fixes.\n\nToday the four sibling callsites (lines 185, 1055, 1191, 1248) are safe because they all insert the provider before any `CreateChat` call, so the cache is never populated without Anthropic. But the ordering dependency is implicit.\n\nCould we add a note to the doc comment? Something like:\n\n```go\n// insertEnabledAnthropicProvider inserts an enabled Anthropic provider for\n// the current test user so computer_use flows keep Anthropic credentials\n// after provider-key pruning. This bypasses the pubsub event that\n// production uses to invalidate configCache; callers that have already\n// triggered cache population (e.g. via CreateChat) must call\n// server.configCache.InvalidateProviders() afterward.\n```\n\n*(Bisky P3, Hisoka P3, Leorio P3)*\n\n> \ud83e\udd16\n\n> \ud83e\udd16 This review was automatically generated with Coder Agents.\n",
